# Regression: the word-operator aliases (`eq`/`equals` -> `==`, `neq` -> `!=`,
# `lt`/`gt`/`lte`/`gte` -> comparisons, `pow` -> `**`) are intentional operator
# spellings, but they must ALSO be usable as plain identifiers wherever an
# identifier is expected: as function names (`*equals`, `*pow`), as parameter
# names, and as bare variables in expression-atom position (`if eq < 0`,
# `total + neq`). Their operator role only fires in infix position, which the
# operator loop consumes before the prefix atom parser is reached, so a
# word-operator that reaches an atom slot is always a genuine name use.
# (`mod` is the sole exception: its token `%` is the address-of prefix operator,
# so `mod` works as a name only through declaration/param positions, never as a
# bare prefix-atom variable — not exercised here.)

*equals(a as i64, b as i64) returns bool
    a equals b

*pow(base as i64, n as i64) returns i64
    result is 1 as i64
    i is 0 as i64
    while i < n
        result is result * base
        i is i + 1
    result

*main
    eq is 5 as i64
    neq is 3 as i64
    total is 0 as i64
    if eq < 0
        total is total + 1
    else
        total is total + eq
    total is total + neq
    if equals(eq, 5)
        total is total + 100
    log(total + pow(2, 3))
